    <h2>When to Send a Review Request by Channel</h2>
    <p><strong>SMS / Text:</strong> Within 1 hour of service. Best between 10am-6pm. Text messages have a 98% open rate, making them the most effective channel for review requests. Keep it under 160 characters (1 SMS segment) to avoid splitting. This tool shows character counts for every SMS template.</p>
    <p><strong>Email:</strong> Within 2 hours of service, or the same business day. Send between 9am-11am or 1pm-3pm for best open rates. Include the review link prominently. Do not bury it in paragraph text. The subject line should be personal and low-pressure.</p>
    <p><strong>In-Person:</strong> At the moment of highest satisfaction. Right after completing the service, while the customer is paying or preparing to leave. Have a QR code displayed at the checkout counter. Train staff on the exact script — confidence matters.</p>
    <p><strong>Follow-Up:</strong> 3-5 days after the initial request. Shorter than the first email. Acknowledge they are busy. Include the link again. For complaint resolutions, wait a full week to ensure the fix is permanent.</p>

    <h2>Review Request Tips by Industry</h2>

    <h3>Dentists & Dental Practices</h3>
    <p>Ask right after the appointment, before the patient leaves the office. The front desk staff should have a script ready. Mention the specific treatment: "Thanks for coming in for your cleaning" feels more personal than "Thanks for your visit." Text messages work especially well for younger patients. For first visits, welcome them to the practice family.</p>

    <h3>Plumbers & HVAC</h3>
    <p>Have your technician ask in person when they finish the job, then follow up with a text within the hour. The customer is most satisfied when the problem is solved. That is your window. "Your drain is flowing perfectly now. Would you mind leaving us a quick Google review?" For repeat customers, acknowledge their loyalty: "Thanks for calling us again."</p>

    <h3>Lawyers & Law Firms</h3>
    <p>Timing is everything in legal. Do not ask during an active case. Ask after a successful resolution. Use a professional tone. Lawyers should be especially careful not to reference case details in review requests. Keep it about the client experience, not the outcome. For first consultations, focus on the quality of the initial advice.</p>

    <h3>Restaurants & Cafes</h3>
    <p>QR codes on the table or receipt are the most natural ask in a restaurant setting. Train servers to mention it when dropping off the check: "If you enjoyed your meal, we would love a quick review. There is a QR code on the table." Do not text or email unless you collect contact info through reservations. For first-time diners, a warm welcome increases review likelihood by 35%.</p>

    <h3>Salons & Spas</h3>
    <p>The mirror moment is your best opportunity. Right after the client sees their new look and loves it — that is when you ask. Have the stylist say: "You look amazing! If you have 30 seconds, a Google review would help other people find us." For repeat clients, reference their transformation journey. "You have been coming to us for a year now — your hair has never looked better!"</p>

